[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Care Coordination Across Many Systems, Many Clinicians, Many Episodes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Been The Last Mile, And Why The Latest Tools Help
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a function, has been understood as a clinical and operational discipline since at least the early 2000s, when the term came into wide use in U.S. healthcare and became a CMS quality measure category. <!-- TODO: verify; care coordination as a recognized clinical and quality-measurement category in U.S. healthcare has been formalized through CMS, NQF, and AHRQ frameworks over the past two-plus decades; specific dates and frameworks vary --> The function exists because the U.S. healthcare delivery system is structurally fragmented: care for any given patient is delivered across multiple organizations, multiple electronic record systems, multiple payers, multiple ancillary services, and multiple administrative workflows that do not natively share information or coordinate state. The fragmentation is not anyone's individual failing; it is a structural feature of how the country built its healthcare delivery and payment systems over the second half of the twentieth century, and the structural reasons it persists are political and economic, not technical.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The patients who feel the fragmentation most are the ones with the most touchpoints: high-utilizer patients with multiple chronic conditions, oncology patients navigating multi-specialty pathways, organ transplant recipients, end-stage renal disease patients, complex pediatric patients, patients with significant social-determinant complexity, and patients with serious mental-illness comorbidity. For these patients, the system does not coordinate itself. Coordination is done by humans (the care manager, the family caregiver, the patient when they are well enough to do it), or it is not done.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The tools the field has used to address fragmentation have come in several waves. The first wave, roughly 1990 to 2010, was electronic medical records: digitize the chart, give clinicians inside one organization a shared view, and improve the documentation. EMR adoption helped within an organization but did very little for cross-organization coordination, because the organizations did not share their EMRs. The second wave, roughly 2005 to 2020, was health information exchange: regional and national infrastructure for sharing clinical data across organizations. HIE adoption has been slow, uneven, and structurally limited by data-quality, identity-matching, governance, and incentive misalignment. <!-- TODO: verify; the U.S. health information exchange landscape including TEFCA, regional HIEs, and major frameworks like Carequality, CommonWell, and Epic Care Everywhere has continued to evolve with varying coverage and clinical utility --> The third wave, roughly 2010 to present, is FHIR and the broader interoperability standards: a structured, queryable API surface for clinical data that, when implemented, lets one system query another system's chart for specific resources. FHIR adoption has accelerated since the ONC Cures Act Final Rule's information-blocking provisions and the certification requirements for FHIR APIs. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR adoption in U.S. healthcare has accelerated since the 2020 ONC Cures Act Final Rule and CMS Patient Access API requirements; specific adoption rates vary by setting and use case --> FHIR helps. FHIR does not, on its own, do care coordination. It provides the data substrate; the synthesis, the workflow, and the patient-and-caregiver-facing experience are not in the standard.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape, again, is large language models that can read across many sources, synthesize, and produce a coherent answer in a conversational interface. A care coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance and integration, can sit on top of the FHIR APIs, the scheduling system, the messaging system, the prior-auth queue, the medication-list reconciliation, the home-health and ancillary-service plans, the care-management-team contact directory, and the patient's stated preferences and concerns, and answer the kind of questions Elena has been answering by hand. The assistant is not interpreting clinical data; it is synthesizing logistical and navigational information that is already in the institution's systems but is scattered.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "patient portal that shows pieces" to "conversational interface that synthesizes and acts on logistics across systems." The assistant's value is concentrated in the synthesis (assembling the picture from many sources), the lower activation-energy access for the patient and caregiver, and the operational-leverage extension for the human care management team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what care-coordination AI is and is not, because the category has language overlap with several adjacent categories. Care navigation is the practice of guiding a patient through a specific care pathway (typically oncology, transplant, or another disease-specific journey); care management is the longitudinal management of a patient's clinical and social complexity, usually by a care manager; care coordination is the cross-cutting function of ensuring that care across the whole care team is coherent. These functions overlap in practice, and the assistant in this recipe touches all three. The assistant is not a replacement for any of them; it is a tool that the patient, the caregiver, and the human care-management team use together.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (longitudinal record, problem list, medications, allergies, active orders, referrals, scheduled appointments, recent encounters, recent messages, recent labs, active prior authorizations, home-health and ancillary-service plans, care-team directory with provider relationships and roles, the patient's stated preferences, the family caregiver designation if any, conversation history), and a comprehensive set of tools for retrieving information across systems, identifying coordination gaps, scheduling logistics, routing questions to the right clinical team, escalating to the care manager, and producing consolidated views.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is, like the chronic-disease coach, a stream of conversational episodes. Patients and caregivers initiate most of them. Some are scheduled (a transitions-of-care follow-up after discharge; a check-in before a major appointment; a referral-status update when a referral has been pending). Some are triggered by events in the integrated systems (an authorization denial; an appointment cancellation; a missed lab; a discrepancy in the medication list across systems; a clinical alert from the care manager).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The assistant's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding and consent.** The patient or caregiver enrolls through the institution's portal, the payer's care-management program, or the health-system's complex-care-program. Consent covers the assistant's nature (it is a chat tool, not a person, and not a replacement for the patient's clinicians or the care manager), its scope (logistics, navigation, synthesis, triage, escalation; not clinical decision-making), the data it accesses (broad longitudinal access across the institution's systems, with patient-controlled scope where applicable), the family-caregiver relationship if any (with the patient designating a caregiver and authorizing the caregiver's access to the assistant under the patient's account), the consent for care-team information sharing (the assistant's interactions surface to the care-management team and, with consent, to the patient's clinicians), and the privacy posture in plain language. State-specific consent variations apply where mental-health-record protections, substance-use-treatment-record protections, or minor consent rules are relevant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Authenticated session entry with disclosure refresh.** Like the previous chapter 11 recipes, every session begins with an explicit disclosure refresh: this is a chat tool, not a person; not a clinician; the care manager and the patient's clinicians are reachable through the appropriate channels; in an emergency, 911. The disclosure refresh sets the relationship and reinforces the boundary.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Continuous safety screening.** Every patient utterance is screened for clinical emergencies (acute symptoms requiring 911 routing), self-harm or crisis-mental-health concerns (routed via the patterns from recipe 11.8), abuse and neglect indicators (with mandatory-reporting routing where required), social-determinant crises (housing instability, food insecurity, transportation collapse, intimate-partner violence) that affect care delivery, and adversarial inputs (prompt injection, social engineering attempts).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Synthesis and surfacing.** The assistant's most distinctive function. The patient or caregiver asks "where do things stand?" and the assistant assembles, from across the integrated systems, what is on the schedule (appointments, procedures, labs, imaging), what is pending (referrals awaiting acceptance, authorizations awaiting approval, records awaiting transmission, lab orders awaiting completion, follow-up tasks awaiting closure), what is overdue (preventive screenings due, lab follow-ups due, refills due, care-plan reviews due), what is current (active medications by indication, problem list with each clinician's role, recent encounters with summary key points), and what the patient or caregiver should be doing next.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Specialist and care-team mapping.** The assistant knows who is doing what for the patient. The assistant can answer "which doctor is handling my heart failure?" and "what does my nephrologist do that's different from my cardiologist?" and "is my primary care doctor in the loop on what the orthopedic surgeon said?" The mapping draws on the institution's provider directory, the patient's specific care relationships, and the institutional understanding of typical multi-specialty roles.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Logistics and operations.** Rescheduling appointments (handing off to recipe 11.2 with context attached). Checking authorization status. Following up on pending referrals. Reconciling the medication list across systems. Surfacing transportation needs and routing to the institution's transportation-benefit support. Surfacing benefits-navigation questions (handing off to recipe 11.5 with context attached). Surfacing prescription-refill needs (handing off to recipe 11.3 with context attached). Surfacing pre-visit intake needs (handing off to recipe 11.4 with context attached). The assistant is the front door to the chapter-11 patient-facing assistant family for complex patients.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-transition support.** When the patient has just been discharged, has just had a major procedure, has just changed primary care, has just transferred care to or from another institution, or has just had a significant care-plan change, the transition window is a high-risk time for coordination failures. The assistant runs through transition-checklists, surfaces specific transition tasks, ensures medication reconciliation has happened, ensures follow-up appointments are scheduled, ensures the patient and caregiver understand the discharge instructions, and escalates anything that has fallen through.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **New-concern triage.** When the patient or caregiver raises a new concern (a new symptom, a side effect of a new medication, a question about a recent encounter, a worry about a behavior change), the assistant routes the concern to the right clinical team. The triage is conservative (when in doubt, escalate to the care manager or the appropriate clinician's office) and is not clinical decision-making. The triage uses patterns from recipe 11.6 (symptom checker / triage) for symptom-driven concerns, with the additional context of the patient's full clinical and care-team picture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management-team collaboration.** The human care-management team is the assistant's primary collaborator and supervisor. The assistant proposes actions; the care manager accepts, modifies, or declines. The assistant generates structured summaries for the care manager. The assistant flags cases for the care manager's attention based on coordination gaps, social-determinant signals, or patient-or-caregiver-distress signals. The assistant runs scheduled outreach the care manager has configured. The assistant does not unilaterally change the care plan; the care manager (in collaboration with the patient's clinicians) does.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver support.** Many high-need patients have an active family caregiver who handles much of the operational burden. The assistant supports the caregiver as a first-class user: with the patient's authorization, the caregiver can access the assistant on the patient's behalf, ask questions about the patient's care plan, surface concerns, request escalation to the care manager, and receive caregiver-targeted content (caregiver-burden assessment, respite resources, caregiver-specific psychoeducation). The architectural distinction between patient-as-user and caregiver-as-user is explicit and audited.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Documentation in the chart.** When the assistant has a meaningful interaction (a triaged concern, a surfaced coordination gap, a documented transition support, a documented caregiver outreach), it produces a structured note for the care manager and (with appropriate clinical-leadership policy) for the patient's chart, documenting what was done, what was surfaced, and what was routed. The chart documentation is institutionally policy-reviewed; the bot is not creating clinical notes that look like clinician notes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding when appropriate.** Some patients become medically stable and no longer need care-coordination support. Some patients move to a different institution. Some patients pass away. The assistant supports a respectful transition with summary delivery to the receiving care team and a clear path back if the patient or caregiver wants to re-engage.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it FHIR access, prompt it as "you are a care coordinator," and let it answer patient questions. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no consistent picture of who is doing what.** Care-team mapping is institutional. The LLM does not know that, in this institution, the cardiologist with admitting privileges manages heart failure for inpatients but the heart-failure clinic NP manages heart failure outpatient, or that this specific cardiologist refers diabetic patients to this specific endocrinologist for shared management. The institutional care-team map is a curated artifact, version-controlled and signed off by the care-management leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents dates, statuses, and details under uncertainty.** Asking the LLM "when is my orthopedic appointment?" and trusting a freestyle answer is dangerous. The architectural floor is structured retrieval through scheduling-system tools, with the answer grounded in retrieved data and never freestyled.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of which system is the source of truth for which fact.** The medication list at the pharmacy and the medication list in the clinic chart can disagree, and the truth depends on the question (what is being dispensed vs. what was prescribed at the most recent encounter). The assistant has institutional rules for source-of-truth selection per fact type, with discrepancies surfaced rather than silently reconciled.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when an authorization has been requested, denied, appealed, or approved.** The authorization status is event-stream-driven and time-sensitive; the LLM does not know the current state without retrieval. The architectural floor is to read from the authorization queue at conversation time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the patient's own scheduling preferences and constraints.** Marisol's daughter Elena drives Marisol to appointments; Elena's work schedule constrains scheduling; Marisol does not drive at night. These constraints are part of the patient's longitudinal record (patient-stated preferences, family-caregiver-stated preferences), and they should inform any scheduling proposal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of clinical scope and the line between coordination and clinical decision-making.** A generalist LLM, asked "should I take the metformin tomorrow because of the contrast CT?", will give a freestyle answer. The right answer is "this is a question for your primary care doctor or the imaging center; let me route the question with the relevant context attached and ensure you get an answer before tomorrow morning." The scope discipline is non-trivial and is reinforced through the system prompt, the output safety, and the sampled review process.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of social determinants as a coordination input.** Transportation collapse, housing instability, food insecurity, and benefits-loss are coordination-affecting events that the assistant should detect and route. The screening for social-determinant signals and the routing to community resources, social work, and benefits navigation is institutional and curated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of mandatory reporting and protected categories.** Some disclosures (abuse, neglect, intimate-partner violence) trigger statutory reporting obligations for licensed clinical staff. Some categories (substance use under 42 CFR Part 2, mental health under state-specific statutes, HIV status, genetic information) have enhanced privacy protections. The assistant routes appropriately and respects the protections; the generalist LLM does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the care manager as the responsible human.** The care manager owns the patient's care plan. The assistant proposes actions to the care manager; the care manager accepts, modifies, or declines. The assistant does not unilaterally close referrals, schedule appointments, change medication lists, or update the problem list; those actions are the human care manager's. The architectural distinction is enforced through tool-permissioning, not through prompt instructions alone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the family caregiver as a distinct authorized user.** The patient is one person; the family caregiver is another. The caregiver's access to the assistant is via the patient's authorization, with audit trail. The caregiver's questions are answered with the patient's data; the patient's questions are answered with the patient's data; the audit log distinguishes which one was asking. Without this distinction, the system cannot demonstrate compliance with the patient's authorization scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of episode boundaries.** A care plan has phases: pre-procedure, procedure, post-procedure, recovery. A maternal care plan has trimesters and a postpartum window. A transplant care plan has pre-transplant evaluation, transplant, immediate post-transplant, and long-term immunosuppression management. The assistant has institutional knowledge of typical episode structures and the patient's specific position in their episodes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of compliance for cross-institution data flows.** When the patient receives care across multiple institutions, data flow between institutions is governed by HIPAA's permitted-disclosures framework, by patient-authorization rules, by 42 CFR Part 2 for substance-use-treatment data, by state-specific statutes, by HIE participation agreements, and by TEFCA-specific rules where applicable. The assistant's data-access posture has to account for each.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when not to engage.** Some questions are outside the assistant's scope: "should I take this medication?" (clinical), "what does this lab mean?" (clinical interpretation), "what is my prognosis?" (clinical), "is my doctor doing the right thing?" (clinical-judgment-of-judgment), "I just want to vent about the system" (out of scope; route to caregiver-support resources or the care manager). The assistant recognizes the boundary and routes; the generalist LLM tries to be helpful and crosses it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Care Coordination Assistant Has To Do That The Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits. Care coordination adds nine new structural commitments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system integration as architectural primitive.** The assistant reads across more systems than any of the previous bots: EHR, scheduling, messaging, prior-auth queue, pharmacy, lab, imaging, home-health-agency record, care-management-platform record, social-determinant assessment record, transportation-benefits, community-resource directory, and (where applicable) cross-institution HIE feeds. The integrations have specific freshness requirements (an authorization status cached for two hours is different from an authorization status read live from the queue), specific failure modes (each integration can fail independently), and specific governance (each integration has data-use-agreement scope).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-as-collaborator pattern.** The human care-management team is the assistant's primary supervisor. The assistant proposes actions to the care manager; the care manager accepts or modifies. The assistant runs scheduled outreach the care manager has configured. The assistant generates summaries for the care manager. The architectural decisions about which actions the assistant can take unilaterally (typically: read-only, surfacing, scheduling within established constraints, routing to existing escalation paths) versus which actions require care-manager approval (typically: anything that changes the care plan, anything that creates a new care-team relationship, anything that closes a coordination gap that requires clinical confirmation) are policy-reviewed and version-controlled.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-mapping as curated artifact.** The institutional understanding of who does what for the patient is a curated artifact: provider-role definitions, specialty-typical-relationship patterns, institution-specific care-pathway descriptions. The assistant uses this artifact rather than freestyling provider relationships from chart data alone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode-aware longitudinal context.** The patient's care plan has phases. The assistant has institutional knowledge of typical episode structures (oncology pathway phases, transplant pathway phases, maternal-care pathway phases, post-discharge transition windows, complex-chronic-disease management phases) and the patient's specific position. The episode-aware context informs what the assistant surfaces and how it prioritizes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver-as-authorized-user pattern.** The family caregiver is a first-class user, with the patient's authorization, with audited access scope, with caregiver-specific content, and with caregiver-burden screening. The architectural distinction between patient and caregiver is preserved throughout the audit and access-control surfaces.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordination-failure detection as scheduled and triggered work.** The assistant runs scheduled scans for coordination gaps (referrals pending too long, authorizations expiring, follow-up appointments not scheduled within the institutional standard, lab orders not completed, medication-reconciliation discrepancies, care-plan-review windows due) and triggers patient outreach, care-manager alerts, or both based on the gap and the institutional response policy. This is more scheduled work than the previous bots, which were primarily reactive to patient-initiated conversations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-institution data-flow discipline.** When the patient receives care across multiple institutions, the assistant's data-access posture is governed by the patient's authorization, the cross-institution agreements, and the protected-category rules. The assistant operates with a clear policy for what it can read, what it can write back, and what it can share between institutions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Documentation-discipline for chart entries.** When the assistant produces a structured note for the care manager or the patient's chart, the note is institutionally formatted, clearly attributed to the assistant (not impersonating a clinician), version-stamped, and reviewed periodically by clinical leadership. The chart-documentation policy is signed off by the relevant clinical-leadership team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational-leverage measurement as a primary success metric.** The assistant's job is to extend the human care-management team's leverage. The primary success metrics include care-manager time saved, panel-size-per-care-manager increased, and care-coordination-failure rates reduced, alongside patient-and-caregiver experience and downstream-utilization metrics. Engagement metrics are secondary and informational.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care-Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care-coordination specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration breadth is the engineering work.** More than any other bot in this chapter, the care-coordination assistant lives or dies by the integrations. Each integration is a project: the EHR integration, the scheduling integration, the prior-auth integration, the pharmacy integration, the home-health-agency integration, the social-determinant-assessment integration, the cross-institution HIE integration. Each has its own contract, its own freshness requirement, its own failure mode, its own data-use scope, and its own governance overhead. The institutional integration-engineering capacity is the rate-limiting input.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The care-team-mapping artifact is institutional curation, not LLM inference.** The mapping of who does what for the patient is a curated artifact, owned by the care-management leadership, reviewed annually, and updated as the institution's care patterns evolve. Institutions discover, partway through the project, that the care-team-mapping artifact does not exist in any consolidated form and has to be built. The build is multi-quarter clinical work with operations, care-management leadership, and the relevant specialty-leadership teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The care-management-team workflow integration is the operational core.** The assistant proposes actions; the care manager accepts or modifies. The care manager's tooling has to support this efficiently, or the assistant becomes a source of inbox burden rather than a source of leverage. The care-manager-tooling design is a primary deliverable, often built alongside or before the patient-facing chat interface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient-and-caregiver experience design is harder than it looks.** Patients with five chronic conditions, an aging cognitive profile, and a family caregiver have very different interaction patterns than patients with a single concern. The interface has to accommodate caregivers operating on the patient's behalf, has to handle long-running conversations across many days, has to surface complex synthesis results in digestible form, has to handle interruption and resumption, and has to respect the patient's stated preferences around tone, frequency, and channel. The patient-experience investment is multi-quarter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome attribution is hard and is multi-year work.** The assistant's effects on care-coordination-failure rates, on caregiver burden, on care-manager leverage, on downstream utilization, and on patient and caregiver satisfaction are observable but require careful measurement design. Engaged patients are not a random sample; care-management-program patients are typically selected for high need, which confounds attribution. Mitigation: matched-cohort or quasi-experimental analysis; recognition that observational correlation is suggestive, not causal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic fit is critical and underestimated.** Care-coordination needs vary by culture, by language, by family structure, by how patients and families relate to clinicians, and by how trust is built. An assistant that operates only in English, only references one cultural framework for family-caregiver dynamics, and only delivers content at one reading level is excluding much of the population it should be serving.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The build-vs-buy market is fragmented.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-management platforms (Salesforce Health Cloud, Innovaccer, Cedar Gate, Apixio, ZeOmega, and others) with care-coordination workflows and (increasingly) AI-augmented features. <!-- TODO: verify; the care-management platform vendor landscape is broad and continues to evolve; specific vendor positioning varies --> Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: leverage a care-management platform for the workflow, build or partner for the patient-facing assistant layer, and integrate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is meaningful.** An assistant that fails to surface a critical coordination gap (a missed cardiology pre-op clearance leading to a cancelled surgery; an expired authorization leading to a delayed treatment; a medication-reconciliation discrepancy leading to a dispensing error) is a foreseeable liability exposure. Mitigation: false-negative-rate monitoring on coordination-gap detection; care-manager-review pathways; institutional malpractice carrier involvement; documented operational policies for what the assistant can and cannot do unilaterally.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Privacy posture is broader than for other bots.** The assistant has read access across many systems. The audit posture, the access-control posture, and the protected-category handling (substance-use treatment under 42 CFR Part 2; mental-health under state-specific statutes; HIV status; genetic information; minor-consent rules) is correspondingly broader. Counsel familiar with multi-source PHI workflows is involved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity considerations are central, not peripheral.** Care-coordination is a high-leverage intervention for patients with the greatest unmet need; those patients are also the most likely to be excluded by digital-only interfaces, English-only content, and middle-class-default assumptions about caregiver availability and family structure. Per-cohort monitoring, multi-channel deployment, and explicit equity-focused design are non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR is the data-substrate baseline.** Patient, Practitioner, Encounter, Condition, MedicationStatement, MedicationRequest, AllergyIntolerance, Observation, Immunization, ServiceRequest, Appointment, ReferralRequest, Coverage, CarePlan, CareTeam, Goal, Communication, and Task are the core resources for care coordination. FHIR Bulk Data Access supports population-level queries. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR R4 and R5 specifications and the specific resource set used in care-coordination implementations are documented at hl7.org; specific resource adoption varies -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA and Carequality are the cross-institution data-flow frameworks in the U.S.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement (TEFCA) provides a national-scale framework for cross-institution data exchange, with Qualified Health Information Networks as the participating entities. Carequality and CommonWell are pre-existing frameworks that interoperate with TEFCA. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA, Carequality, and CommonWell governance, participation, and use-case scope continue to evolve; specific operational details vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **CMS Patient Access API requirements are in effect.** Medicare Advantage organizations, Medicaid Fee-for-Service programs, Medicaid managed-care plans, CHIP, and qualified health plans on the federal exchanges are required to provide a FHIR-based Patient Access API exposing claims data, encounter data, formulary data, and clinical data. <!-- TODO: verify; CMS Patient Access API and Provider Directory API requirements were established in the CMS Interoperability and Patient Access Final Rule; specific compliance dates and scope vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **ONC Cures Act Final Rule's information-blocking provisions affect institutional behavior.** Healthcare actors (providers, IT developers, HIEs, HINs) are subject to information-blocking penalties for practices that interfere with the access, exchange, or use of electronic health information, with specific exceptions. <!-- TODO: verify; the ONC Cures Act Final Rule and the information-blocking provisions are documented at HealthIT.gov; specific enforcement actions and exceptions continue to evolve --> The institutional posture is more permissive of cross-institution data flows than it was a decade ago.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management platforms have integrated AI features.** Several major care-management platforms have added LLM-powered features for summarization, case prioritization, and patient outreach. <!-- TODO: verify; specific AI features in commercial care-management platforms continue to evolve --> Build-vs-buy decisions account for the platform's AI features as a starting point.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle care-coordination synthesis well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that read FHIR resources, query the scheduling system, query the prior-auth queue, query the medication list across systems, retrieve the care-team map, propose care-manager actions, schedule outreach, and produce structured documentation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinant integration is a maturing surface.** Z-codes (ICD-10-CM Z55-Z65) provide a structured vocabulary for social-determinant documentation. Several validated screening instruments exist (PRAPARE, AHC HRSN screening tool, others). <!-- TODO: verify; Z-codes for social determinants of health and validated screening instruments including PRAPARE and the AHC HRSN screening tool are documented in CMS, AHRQ, and academic resources --> Community-resource directories (Aunt Bertha / findhelp, Unite Us, regional 211 services, others) provide structured access to community resources for routing. <!-- TODO: verify; community-resource-directory integrations are available through specific commercial and non-profit vendors with varying coverage and quality -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Specialty pathways are increasingly codified.** Oncology care pathways (NCCN guidelines, institutional pathways), transplant care pathways (UNOS-aligned), maternal-care pathways (ACOG-aligned), and others are increasingly codified at the institutional level. The codification supports episode-aware care coordination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
